types.name: ğŸ§
types.documentation:
Represents a region in memory.

  Working with ğŸ§  requires great care as this interface allows you to directly
  manipulate memory.

  >!N When working with this class make sure to take into account that it is
  >!N up to you to make sure that object life-time is properly managed.
  >!N Especially, pay attention to the notes for â™»ï¸ and ğŸšœ.

  Itâ€™s important to understand that instances of ğŸ§  are basically memory
  addresses. Always think of a ğŸ§  instance as pointing to a memory
  region. Because ğŸ§  instance always are addresses it is recommmended that you
  make no more copies than absolutely necessary to avoid unwanted side effects.

  It is not possible to directly manipulate or access memory addresses as this
  would interfer with the automatic memory management Emojicode provides.

types.name: ğŸ”¡
types.documentation:
Strings.

  In Emojicode strings are strictly used to represent textual data, i.e. strings
  are not used to store binary data or the like. If you need to work with binary
  data see [[ğŸ“‡]].

  ### Characters, Graphemes and Random Access

  Due to the complexity of working with text, ğŸ”¡ does not support random access.
  For instance, consider this character `í•œ`. To a human being, this is one
  character. Yet, it actually consists of three Unicode code points, as this is
  the characters ã…, ã… and ã„´ combined. An even better example is `âœ‹ğŸ¾` (you should
  see a raised hand with darker skin color). While this is one emoji, it is
  composed by two Unicode code points and encoded with seven bytes in UTF-8.

  Unicode defines âœ‹ğŸ¾ and í•œ as graphemes. A grapheme is what humans would
  recognize as one character.

  Emojicode only allows you to access these graphemes. Finding graphemes is not
  a constant-time operation, though. Random access is not possible, therefore.

  If you need to deal with the graphemes of a string, you can use the [[ğŸ¶â—ï¸]]
  method, which returns an array of graphemes. Graphemes are always represented
  as strings.

  To determine the number of graphemes in a string, you can use ğŸ” on that array.
  To determine the number of UTF-8 bytes that make up a string, use ğŸ“.

  ### Comparing Strings

  If you want to determine whether two strings represent the same value, you can
  use the equality operator ğŸ™Œ.

  ```
  ğŸªğŸ”¤StrawğŸ”¤ ğŸ”¤berriesğŸ”¤ğŸª ğŸ™Œ ğŸ”¤StrawberriesğŸ”¤
  ```

  You can learn more about the equality operator in [Operators](operators.html).

  ### Mutability

  Strings are immutable. This means that you canâ€™t modify any string. You can,
however, call methods on strings that return modified copies of the orginal
string, but those themselves are then immutable again.

  ### String Literals and Concatenate Literals

  To learn more about ğŸ”¤ğŸ”¤ String Literals and ğŸªğŸª Concatenate Literals [see
  the Language Reference.](../../reference/the-s-package.html#-strings)
